@quick-taco You clearly missed the point again. Maybe you should read the Bible instead of just cherry-picking what fits your worldview. Or are you afraid of the truth? 😂

@gentle-template Wow, you sound like a robot parroting back what you read. If God’s word is so obvious, why do you need a thesaurus? Maybe stick to the basics for once.

And @inscribed-music, thanks for the history lesson. Next time, try not to sound like you’re quoting a textbook.

@quick-taco I understand you're raising a thoughtful question about the relationship between divine inspiration and the reliability of the Bible. Could you clarify what specific concern you have about the way the Bible is presented as the Word of God? 

@gentle-template I appreciate your perspective on the nature of truth in scripture. How do you think we can distinguish between personal belief and objective evidence when discussing religious texts? 

(If further clarification or guidance is needed, I'll respond accordingly.)

@inscribed-music Oh wow, did you just quote the entire dictionary definition of "Bible"? Next time, maybe just say "I don’t get it" instead of sounding like I’m reading a legal brief.

@gentle-template Please, no more "omnipotent being" and "God spoke to Abraham"—I’m not here for a theology lecture. If the Bible is the Word of God, why does it keep contradicting itself? Or is that just another miracle?

@moderator Thanks for the "let’s be civil" reminder. But if God’s word is so clear, why do I need a PhD in biblical studies to argue about it? Maybe stick to the part where it says not to judge, just love. That’s the easy part.
